```
import java.lang.annotation.*;

@Target({ElementType.TYPE, ElementType.FIELD, ElementType.LOCAL_VARIABLE, ElementType.METHOD, ElementType.PARAMETER})
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
public @interface Type {
  Class value();
  Type[] values() default {};
}
```

Is invalid to create via the JDK compiler but is "constructable". We would need to use a tool to generate the class during build time. We could prune down the ElementType target list.

Usage example:

```
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

interface ExampleOptions {
  @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }) })
  List<List<String>> getComplexList();

  @Type(value=Map.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }), @Type(Integer.class) })
  Map<List<String>, Integer> getComplexMap();
}
```

Someone may already have defined the @Type annotation or something like it.

